31 #define DEFAULT_ACL_PACKET_TYPE (HCI_PKT_DM1 | HCI_PKT_DH1 | HCI_PKT_DM3 | HCI_PKT_DH3 | HCI_PKT_DM5 | HCI_PKT_DH5)
32 #define DEFAULT_SCO_PACKET_TYPE (HCI_PKT_HV3)
33 
34 /* dm_prim_t allocation
35  *
36  * 0x0000 -> 0x0100 HCI events
37  * 0x0100 -> 0x0180 RESERVED
38  * 0x0180 -> 0x0200 DM_INTERNAL (RESERVED for internal DM communication)
39  * 0x0200 -> 0x0280 DM_AMPM
40  * 0x0280 -> 0x0300 DM_SYNC
41  * 0x0300 -> 0x0380 DM_PRIV
42  * 0x0380 -> 0x0400 DM_SM
43  * 0x0400 -> HCI commands
44  * (but bit 10 - 0x0200 - which is the top bit of the OGC is used to indicate
45  * whether the command requires a connection handle to be filled in by the DM)
46  */
47 
48 /* send_to_hci_with_handle */
49 #define DM_HCI_WITH_HANDLE 0x0200
50 #define DM_HCI_OP_CODE_MASK (~DM_HCI_WITH_HANDLE)
51 
52 /* DM_HCI_ types */
53 #define DM_HCI_EVENT_PRIM 0x0010
54 #define DM_LC_PRIM HCI_LINK
55 #define DM_LP_PRIM HCI_POLICY
56 #define DM_BB_PRIM HCI_HOST_BB
57 #define DM_INF_PRIM HCI_INFO
58 #define DM_STATUS_PRIM HCI_STATUS
59 #define DM_TEST_PRIM HCI_TEST
60 #define DM_ULP_PRIM HCI_ULP
61 #define DM_OGF_MASK 0xFC00
62 #define DM_HCI_COMMANDS DM_LC_PRIM
63 
64 /* DM types used internally - not exported to the application. */
65 #define DM_INTERNAL_DOWN_PRIM 0x0180
66 #define DM_INTERNAL_UP_PRIM 0x01C0
67 #define DM_INERNAL_PRIM DM_INTERNAL_DOWN_PRIM
68 /* Native DM types - not DM_HCI_ */
69 /* AMPM interface to DM */
70 #define DM_AMPM_DOWN_PRIM 0x0200
71 #define DM_AMPM_UP_PRIM 0x0240
72 #define DM_AMPM_PRIM DM_AMPM_DOWN_PRIM
73 /* SCO primitives */
74 #define DM_SYNC_DOWN_PRIM 0x0280
75 #define DM_SYNC_UP_PRIM 0x02C0
76 #define DM_SYNC_PRIM DM_SYNC_DOWN_PRIM
77 /* Commands specific to this Device Manager */
78 #define DM_PRIV_DOWN_PRIM 0x0300
79 #define DM_PRIV_UP_PRIM 0x0340
80 #define DM_PRIV_PRIM DM_PRIV_DOWN_PRIM
81 /* Security manager primitives */
82 #define DM_SM_DOWN_PRIM 0x0380
83 #define DM_SM_UP_PRIM 0x03C0
84 #define DM_SM_PRIM DM_SM_DOWN_PRIM

93  /* DM_AM_REGISTER_REQ for old API.
94 
95  This is just to help catch an application sending DM_AM_REGISTER_REQ
96  using the wrong API. If you do this from the VM (which should be
97  quite difficult) then the firmware will panic. If you do it via an
98  external physical interface (setting the top bit of the phandle) then
99  the firmware will reply with INVALID_PHANDLE.*/
100  ENUM_DM_AM_REGISTER_WRONG_API_REQ = 0,
101  ENUM_DM_AM_REGISTER_WRONG_API_CFM = 1,

1321 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*

1338 } DM_AM_REGISTER_WRONG_API_REQ_T;
1339 
1340 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
1341  * PURPOSE
1342  * Confirmation that the registration request has been received.
1343  *
1344  * RETURNS
1345  * phandle specified in DM_AM_REGISTER_REQ.
1346  * Bluestack version. MSB is major version, LSB is minor version.
1347  * Bluestack patchlevel. This is incremented for every release
1348  * with a given Bluestack version number and reset to zero for new
1349  * Bluestack version numbers.
1350  *
1351  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1352 typedef struct
1353 {
1354  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_AM_REGISTER_CFM */
1355  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
1356  uint16_t version; /* Bluestack version */
1357  uint16_t patch_level; /* Bluestack patch level */
1358 } DM_AM_REGISTER_CFM_T;
1359 
1360 typedef struct
1361 {
1362  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_AM_REGISTER_WRONG_API_CFM */
1363  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
1364 } DM_AM_REGISTER_WRONG_API_CFM_T;
1365 
1366 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
1367  * PURPOSE
1368  * Set Bluetooth version. On successful completion, status will
1369  * be set to HCI_SUCCESS == 0 and version will be set to the
1370  * BT version requested. On unsuccessful completion, status will
1371  * be set to an HCI error code and version will be set to the
1372  * current version.
1373  *
1374  * You can use this command to read the current BT version by
1375  * setting version to BT_VERSION_CURRENT in the command primitive.
1376  * (In this case a failure indication in the status parameter would
1377  * be unusual and would indicate that the current version settings
1378  * are no longer supported by the device.)
1379  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1380 
1381 #define BT_VERSION_CURRENT 0x00
1382 #define BT_VERSION_2p0 0x01
1383 #define BT_VERSION_2p1 0x02
1384 #define BT_VERSION_3p0 0x03
1385 #define BT_VERSION_4p0 0x04
1386 #define BT_VERSION_4p1 0x05
1387 #define BT_VERSION_4p2 0x06
1388 #define BT_VERSION_5p0 0x07
1389 #define BT_VERSION_5p1 0x08
1390 #define BT_VERSION_MAX BT_VERSION_5p1
1391 
1392 
1393 typedef struct
1394 {
1395  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_SET_BT_VERSION_REQ */
1396  uint8_t version; /* Requested version */
1397 } DM_SET_BT_VERSION_REQ_T;
1398 
1399 typedef struct
1400 {
1401  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_SET_BT_VERSION_CFM */
1402  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
1403  uint8_t version; /* Requested version if success, */
1404  uint8_t status; /* or current version if failure */
1405 } DM_SET_BT_VERSION_CFM_T;
1406 
1407 /*------------------------------------------------------------------------
1408  * PURPOSE
1409  * Indication sent to phandle registered with DM_AM_REGISTER_REQ when
1410  * Bluestack receives a message to which it cannot respond in the
1411  * usual fashion. This might be because the message is not recognised
1412  * or because there is no obvious phandle to use for the reply. In
1413  * these cases, Bluestack will send DM_BAD_MESSAGE_IND.
1414  *-----------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1415 
1416 /* Reasons */
1417 #define DM_BAD_MESSAGE_NO_PHANDLE ((uint16_t)0x0001)
1418 #define DM_BAD_MESSAGE_NOT_RECOGNISED ((uint16_t)0x0002)
1419 
1420 typedef struct
1421 {
1422  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_BAD_MESSAGE_IND */

1647 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
1648  *
1649  * SECURITY MANAGEMENT INTERFACE
1650  *
1651  * Downstream primitives are sent to the DM_IFACEQUEUE, upstream primitives
1652  * are sent either to the registered AM queue (see DM_AM_REGISTER_REQ), or to
1653  * the queue of the protocol layer requesting access (for DM_SM_ACCESS_REQ).
1654  * There is a private L2CAP/SM interface for controlling security of received
1655  * connectionless packets.
1656  *
1657  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1658 
1659 typedef uint8_t dm_security_mode_t;
1660 #define SEC_MODE0_OFF ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x00)
1661 #define SEC_MODE1_NON_SECURE ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x01)
1662 #define SEC_MODE2_SERVICE ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x02)
1663 #define SEC_MODE3_LINK ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x03)
1664 #define SEC_MODE4_SSP ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x04)
1665 /*
1666  SEC_MODE2a_DEVICE is a custom security mode that authenticates on a per
1667  device basis using the Security Manager's device database.
1668  On starting a new service (incoming and outgoing), the device will be
1669  authenticated unless it is marked as 'trusted' in the device database
1670  (see DM_SM_ADD_DEVICE_REQ).
1671 */
1672 #define SEC_MODE2a_DEVICE ((dm_security_mode_t) 0x80)
1673 
1674 /* Security level settings
1675  *
1676  * SECL_(IN|OUT)_AUTHORISATION (both mode 4 and legacy)
1677  * Results in a DM_SM_AUTHORISE_IND on a connection attempt from a
1678  * device that is not marked as 'trusted' in the device database.
1679  *
1680  * SECL_(IN|OUT)_AUTHENTICATION (legacy)
1681  * For connections where at least one of the devices is not in mode 4
1682  * (i.e. it's a legacy device) then the legacy pairing procedure
1683  * should be used. The users may have to enter PINs.
1684  *
1685  * SECL_(IN|OUT)_ENCRYPTION (legacy)
1686  * This setting indicates that the link should be encrypted after legacy
1687  * authentication.
1688  *
1689  * SECL4_(IN|OUT)_SSP (mode 4)
1690  * For connections where both devices are in mode 4, Secure Simple Pairing
1691  * is used to generate a shared link key and the link is then encrypted. Only
1692  * SDP is allowed not to have these bits set. All other services must set
1693  * them to achieve compliance.
1694  *
1695  * SECL4_(IN|OUT)_MITM (mode 4)
1696  * For connections where both devices are in mode 4, Secure Simple Pairing
1697  * is used to generate a shared authenticated link key and the link is
1698  * then encrypted. If you set this then you should also set
1699  * SECL4_(IN|OUT)_SSP as it is implied.
1700  *
1701  * SECL4_(IN|OUT)_NO_LEGACY
1702  * Don't support legacy security procedures. This is a mode4-only setting.
1703  * By setting this, you are preventing the device from using legacy pairing
1704  * procedures to authenticate with remote devices that do not support
1705  * simple pairing. If you set this then the device will be
1706  * incapable of pairing using legacy procedures and so will reject all
1707  * connection attempts with legacy devices where security is required.
1708  * If you set this then you may severely reduce interoperability.
1709  *
1710  */
1711 
1712 typedef uint16_t dm_security_level_t;
1713 
1714 /* BR/EDR security levels */
1715 #define SECL_NONE ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0000)
1716 #define SECL_IN_AUTHORISATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0001)
1717 #define SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0002)
1718 #define SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0004)
1719 #define SECL_OUT_AUTHORISATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0008)
1720 #define SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0010)
1721 #define SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0020)
1722 
1723 #define SECL4_IN_SSP ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0100)
1724 #define SECL4_IN_MITM ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0200)
1725 #define SECL4_IN_NO_LEGACY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0400)
1726 #define SECL4_OUT_SSP ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0800)
1727 #define SECL4_OUT_MITM ((dm_security_level_t) 0x1000)
1728 #define SECL4_OUT_NO_LEGACY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x2000)
1729 
1730 #define SECL4_IN_P256_ONLY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x4000)
1731 #define SECL4_OUT_P256_ONLY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x8000)
1732 
1733 /*
1734  * BR/EDR Security Levels defined in Vol 3, Part C, Section 5.2.2.5 of BT2.1
1735  * Spec
1736  *
1737  * N.B. These only affect authentication and encryption. Authorisation is
1738  * separate.
1739  */
1740 /* No security - permitted for SDP only */
1741 #define SECL4_IN_LEVEL_0 SECL_NONE
1742 #define SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_0 SECL_NONE
1743 #define SECL4_LEVEL_0 (SECL4_IN_LEVEL_0 | SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_0)
1744 /* Low security */
1745 #define SECL4_IN_LEVEL_1 SECL4_IN_SSP
1746 #define SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_1 SECL4_OUT_SSP
1747 #define SECL4_LEVEL_1 (SECL4_IN_LEVEL_1 | SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_1)
1748 /* Medium security */
1749 #define SECL4_IN_LEVEL_2 (SECL4_IN_SSP | SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION \
1750  | SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION)
1751 #define SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_2 (SECL4_OUT_SSP | SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION \
1752  | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION)
1753 #define SECL4_LEVEL_2 (SECL4_IN_LEVEL_2 | SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_2)
1754 /* High security */
1755 #define SECL4_IN_LEVEL_3 (SECL4_IN_SSP | SECL4_IN_MITM \
1756  | SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION | SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION)
1757 #define SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_3 (SECL4_OUT_SSP | SECL4_OUT_MITM \
1758  | SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION)
1759 #define SECL4_LEVEL_3 (SECL4_IN_LEVEL_3 | SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_3)
1760 
1761 /* Secure connections security level 4 - P256-based algorithms only */
1762 #define SECL4_IN_LEVEL_4 (SECL4_IN_SSP | SECL4_IN_MITM \
1763  | SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION | SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION \
1764  | SECL4_IN_NO_LEGACY | SECL4_IN_P256_ONLY)
1765 #define SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_4 (SECL4_OUT_SSP | SECL4_OUT_MITM \
1766  | SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION \
1767  | SECL4_OUT_NO_LEGACY | SECL4_OUT_P256_ONLY)
1768 #define SECL4_LEVEL_4 (SECL4_IN_LEVEL_4 | SECL4_OUT_LEVEL_4)
1769 /*
1770  * Security level combinations useful internally
1771  */
1772 /* Incoming security settings */
1773 #define SECL_IN (SECL_IN_AUTHORISATION | SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION \
1774  | SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION | SECL4_IN_SSP | SECL4_IN_MITM \
1775  | SECL4_IN_NO_LEGACY | SECL4_IN_P256_ONLY)
1776 
1777 /* Outgoing security settings */
1778 #define SECL_OUT (SECL_OUT_AUTHORISATION | SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION \
1779  | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION | SECL4_OUT_SSP | SECL4_OUT_MITM \
1780  | SECL4_OUT_NO_LEGACY | SECL4_OUT_P256_ONLY)
1781 
1782 /* Authorisation required (either in or out) */
1783 #define SECL_AUTHORISATION (SECL_IN_AUTHORISATION | SECL_OUT_AUTHORISATION)
1784 
1785 /* Authentication required (legacy) */
1786 #define SECL_AUTHENTICATION (SECL_IN_AUTHENTICATION \
1787  | SECL_OUT_AUTHENTICATION | SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION)
1788 
1789 /* Encryption required (legacy) */
1790 #define SECL_ENCRYPTION (SECL_IN_ENCRYPTION | SECL_OUT_ENCRYPTION)
1791 
1792 /* Simple Secure Pairing required (either in or out) */
1793 #define SECL4_SSP (SECL4_IN_SSP | SECL4_OUT_SSP | SECL4_IN_MITM \
1794  | SECL4_OUT_MITM)
1795 
1796 /* MITM protection required in mode 4 (either in or out) */
1797 #define SECL4_MITM (SECL4_IN_MITM | SECL4_OUT_MITM)
1798 
1799 /* Legacy pairing prohibited in mode 4 (either in or out) */
1800 #define SECL4_NO_LEGACY (SECL4_IN_NO_LEGACY | SECL4_OUT_NO_LEGACY)
1801 
1802 /* Mask of legacy mode settings */
1803 #define SECL_MODE_LEGACY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x007F)
1804 
1805 /* P256 security required in mode 4 (either in or out) */
1806 #define SECL4_P256_ONLY (SECL4_IN_P256_ONLY | SECL4_OUT_P256_ONLY)
1807 
1808 /* The default security level, applied in security modes 2, 3 and 4 when no
1809  * specific security level has been registered for a service. This is set to
1810  * require authentication and encryption of both incoming and outgoing
1811  * connections. It also requires authorisation of incoming connections.
1812  * It may be overridden at run-time using the DM_SET_DEFAULT_SECURITY_REQ
1813  * primitive.
1814  */
1815 #define SECL_DEFAULT (SECL_IN_AUTHORISATION | SECL4_LEVEL_2)
1816 
1817 /* LE Service Security Requirements
1818  *
1819  * Following are basic security requirements defined for LE services.
1820  * Security levels of services are defined using combination of these
1821  * requirements.
1822  * Since BR/EDR and LE security levels cannot be mapped one on one,
1823  * these defined values shall be used for LE services in DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ_T
1824  *
1825  */
1826 #define SEC_LE_NONE ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0000)
1827 #define SEC_LE_IN_ENCRYPTION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0001)
1828 #define SEC_LE_IN_AUTHORISATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0002)
1829 #define SEC_LE_OUT_ENCRYPTION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0004)
1830 #define SEC_LE_OUT_AUTHORISATION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0008)
1831 #define SEC_LE_ENCRYPTION (SEC_LE_IN_ENCRYPTION | SEC_LE_OUT_ENCRYPTION)
1832 #define SEC_LE_AUTHORISATION (SEC_LE_IN_AUTHORISATION | SEC_LE_OUT_AUTHORISATION)
1833 
1834 /* LE Authentication levels */
1835 #define SEC_LE_MITM ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0100)
1836 #define SEC_LE_SECURE_CONNECTION ((dm_security_level_t) 0x0200)
1837 
1838 #define SEC_LE_128_BIT_ENC_KEY ((dm_security_level_t) 0x1000)
1839 
1840 /* LE security levels
1841  * These security levels are mapped to LE GAP security levels from specification
1842  * Ref : Version 4.2 [Vol 3, Part C] Sec 10.2.1
1843  *
1844  * When device is put to SC only mode, all the services security requirement
1845  * will considered to be SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_4 while evaluating the security,
1846  * except for services which requires no encryption(level 1).
1847  *
1848  * Important note : It is recommended that applictions use these security
1849  * levels to avoid interoperability issues unless services has very specific
1850  * security requirements which cannot be mapped to GAP security level.
1851  */
1852 #define SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_1 (SEC_LE_NONE)
1853 #define SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_2 (SEC_LE_ENCRYPTION)
1854 #define SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_3 (SEC_LE_MITM | SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_2)
1855 #define SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_4 (SEC_LE_SECURE_CONNECTION | SEC_LE_128_BIT_ENC_KEY | \
1856  SEC_LE_MODE1_LEVEL_3)
1857 
1858 /* Custom security requirements, which cannot be mapped to GAP security level.
1859  * Since there is no equivalent GAP security requirement it recommended to use
1860  * these requirements with caution to avoid iop problems */
1861 
1862 /* SEC_LE_NO_LEGACY ensures that service will only be connected with remote
1863  * devices which are paired using LESC pairing */
1864 #define SEC_LE_NO_LEGACY (SEC_LE_SECURE_CONNECTION)
1865 
1866 /* List of error codes related to LE service security */
1867 #define DM_GAP_LE_ERROR_BASE ((uint8_t)0xE0)
1868 
1869 #define DM_GAP_LE_ERR_INSUFF_AUTHENTICATION ((uint8_t)(DM_GAP_LE_ERROR_BASE))
1870 #define DM_GAP_LE_ERR_INSUFF_ENCRYPTION ((uint8_t)(DM_GAP_LE_ERROR_BASE + 1))
1871 #define DM_GAP_LE_ERR_INSUFF_KEY_SIZE ((uint8_t)(DM_GAP_LE_ERROR_BASE + 2))
1872 #define DM_GAP_LE_ERR_INSUFF_AUTHORIZATION ((uint8_t)(DM_GAP_LE_ERROR_BASE + 3))
1873 
1874

1887 /* Standard security protocol identifiers provided by Bluestack. Higher
1888  * multiplexing protocols must define their own identifiers, from the range
1889  * SEC_PROTOCOL_USER and above.
1890  */
1891 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_NONE ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x0000)
1892 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_SM_BONDING ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x0001)
1893 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_L2CAP ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x0002)
1894 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_RFCOMM ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x0003)
1895 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_LE_L2CAP ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x0004)
1896 
1897 /* Protocol modifier bit for internal use only. This will only be used
1898  by RFCOMM when passing its security requirements through L2CAP. It
1899  has been found that this causes issues with legacy timeout problems.
1900  Setting this bit in the security protocol id passed to the security
1901  manager in a DM_SM_ACCESS_REQ will cause it not to enforce legacy
1902  security. See B-98570. */
1903 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_MODIFY_SSP_ONLY ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x4000)
1904 
1905 /* Higher layers base their protocol IDs from here */
1906 #define SEC_PROTOCOL_USER ((dm_protocol_id_t) 0x8000)
1907 
1908 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
1909  * PURPOSE
1910  * Registers the security requirements for access to a service or a
1911  * multiplexing protocol layer when the Security Manager is in security
1912  * mode 2 or 3. The registered security level is applied to all incoming
1913  * connections on the specified 'channel', and optionally to all outgoing
1914  * connections on that channel if 'outgoing_ok' is TRUE.
1915  *
1916  * It does not always make sense to apply security to outgoing connections,
1917  * for example a local RFCOMM server channel is only valid for incoming
1918  * connections. An L2CAP PSM, however, may be valid in both directions.
1919  * Therefore use the 'outgoing_ok' flag to specify whether security
1920  * should be applied to outgoing connections as well as incoming.
1921  * When the local and remote L2CAP PSMs are different, the local PSM should
1922  * be passed to the Security Manager. For outgoing connections where the
1923  * channel may be different for each remote device, security requirements
1924  * may be registered using the DM_SM_REGISTER_OUTGOING_REQ primitive.
1925  *
1926  * LE services can register the security levels required for the service
1927  * to operate using the same API, since the GAP security levels of BR/EDR
1928  * and LE cannot be mapped one to one, new set of values are defined for
1929  * security_level to be used in registration for LE services,can be
1930  * referred under "LE Service Security Requirements" section above.
1931  *
1932  * NOTE
1933  * The Security Manager enforces a default security level in modes 2,
1934  * 3 and 4 given by the SECL_DEFAULT definition. Any access request
1935  * for which there is no registered security level will be subject to
1936  * the default security. Therefore it is recommended that certain
1937  * services and protocols are always registered with no security,
1938  * for example, SDP and RFCOMM. In Security mode 4, no service, other
1939  * than SDP, should be registered with no security.
1940  *
1941  * If 'channel' is set to 0 then the security manager will choose
1942  * a channel itself. It starts from 0xFFFF and works its way down
1943  * until it finds the first unused channel for the protocol in
1944  * question. This is currently only used for profiles that are
1945  * RFCOMM clients but not servers.
1946  *
1947  * LE has only 1 security mode which can be used by services, as of now
1948  * there is no way applications can set default security mode and
1949  * security levels.
1950  *
1951  * Some security examples are presented:
1952  *
1953  * Eg 1 - A TCS Terminal registers with 'protocol_id' = SEC_PROTOCOL_L2CAP,
1954  * 'channel' = 7 (cordless telephony PSM), and 'outgoing_ok' = TRUE. Then
1955  * L2CAP will request access from the Security Manager for all connections,
1956  * incoming and outgoing, on PSM 7.
1957  *
1958  * Eg 2 - A headset profile might register with 'protocol_id' =
1959  * SEC_PROTOCOL_RFCOMM, 'channel' = the RFCOMM server channel number of the
1960  * headset service, and 'outgoing_ok' = FALSE. Then RFCOMM will request
1961  * access from the Security Manager for all incoming connections on that
1962  * server channel. Access requests for outgoing connections will be
1963  * subjected to the default security level.
1964  *
1965  * Eg 3 - As for (Eg 2), but whenever the profile makes an outgoing
1966  * connection to an Audio Gateway it first performs service discovery to
1967  * obtain the server channel number on the AG device, then registers using
1968  * the DM_SM_REGISTER_OUTGOING_REQ primitive with 'protocol_id' =
1969  * SEC_PROTOCOL_RFCOMM, 'channel' = remote server channel, 'bd_addr' =
1970  * device address of the AG. When the outgoing connection is started,
1971  * RFCOMM will request access from the Security Manager which will apply
1972  * the security level registered for the outgoing connection. Incoming
1973  * connections proceed as in (Eg 2).
1974  *
1975  * Eg 4 - An application can specify the security requirements for access
1976  * to RFCOMM by sending DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ with 'protocol_id' =
1977  * SEC_PROTOCOL_L2CAP, 'channel' = 3, and 'outgoing_ok' = TRUE. Then L2CAP
1978  * will request access from the Security Manager for all new RFCOMM
1979  * connections.
1980  *
1981  * Eg 5 - An application can specify the security requirements for access
1982  * to LE connection oriented channels(L2CAP) by sending DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ
1983  * with 'protocol_id' = SEC_PROTOCOL_LE_L2CAP, 'channel' = 0xf, and
1984  * 'outgoing_ok' = TRUE. Then L2CAP will request access from the Security
1985  * Manager for all new L2CAP LE connections for PSM = 0xf.
1986  *
1987  * min_enc_key_size
1988  * Minimum length of the encryption key size to access the service.
1989  * Applications can configure the min_enc_key_size from range
1990  * 1 to 16 octets for the service using DM_SM_SERVICE_REGISTER_REQ_T
1991  * or DM_SM_SERVICE_REGISTER_OUTGOING_REQ_T primitive.
1992  * If the value is zero then it will be automatically set to default
1993  * DEFAULT_ENC_KEY_SIZE_VAL.
1994  *
1995  * For Services registered through DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ_T or
1996  * DM_SM_REGISTER_OUTGOING_REQ_T primitive the minimum length of
1997  * the encryption key size will be set to DEFAULT_ENC_KEY_SIZE_VAL.
1998  *
1999  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2000 typedef struct
2001 {
2002  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ */
2003  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
2004  context_t context; /* Opaque context */
2005  DM_SM_SERVICE_T service; /* Protocol and channel */
2006  bool_t outgoing_ok; /* TRUE if applies to outgoing */
2007  dm_security_level_t security_level; /* Level of security to be applied */
2008 } DM_SM_REGISTER_REQ_T;
2009 
2010 typedef struct
2011 {
2012  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_SM_SERVICE_REGISTER_REQ */
2013  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
2014  context_t context; /* Opaque context */
2015  DM_SM_SERVICE_T service; /* Protocol and channel */
2016  bool_t outgoing_ok; /* TRUE if applies to outgoing */
2017  dm_security_level_t security_level; /* Level of security to be applied */
2018  uint8_t min_enc_key_size; /* Min enc key size to access the service */
2019 } DM_SM_SERVICE_REGISTER_REQ_T;

2166 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2167  * PURPOSE
2168  * Initialise Security Manager. The result is returned in a
2169  * DM_SM_INIT_CFM primitive.
2170  *
2171  * It is recommended that this is used once as part of the device
2172  * initialisation, but it can be used multiple times using the 'options'
2173  * field to specify which parameters are being initialised.
2174  *
2175  * It is recommended that the security mode is changed only when the
2176  * system is not in the process of creating or accepting any new
2177  * connections. A device conforming to Bluetooth 2.0 or earlier must
2178  * never enter Security Mode 4. A device conforming to Bluetooth 2.1
2179  * or later must enter Security Mode 4 before making itself connectable
2180  * or discoverable and before initiating any connections. It is
2181  * recommended that a device conforming to Bluetooth 2.1 or later
2182  * should enter Security Mode 4 as part of its initialisation process.
2183  *
2184  * Mode 0 is for use by applications which perform their own security
2185  * procedures. The service database is unused in this mode, whereas the
2186  * device database is used only for link keys. Unknown link keys result in
2187  * a link key request being forwarded to the application. This is the
2188  * default mode at startup.
2189  *
2190  * In mode 1, the Security Manager automatically accepts all access
2191  * requests without initiating authentication, encryption, or
2192  * authorisation procedures. Any attempt by an application to perform
2193  * authentication or encryption procedures will be rejected. The Security
2194  * Manager will respond to peer-invoked security procedures as for mode 2.
2195  *
2196  * In mode 2, access requests are subject to the security requirements
2197  * registered in the service and device databases. The Security Manager
2198  * will respond to link key requests using the device database - if a link
2199  * key is unknown, the request is forwarded to the application. PIN code
2200  * requests are forwarded to the application. The application may invoke
2201  * security procedures in this mode.
2202  *
2203  * In mode 3, the host controller is configured to perform authentication
2204  * and possibly encryption at LMP link setup. The Security Manager still
2205  * uses the service database to control authorisation and encryption.
2206  * The encryption level for mode 3 is specified in 'mode3_enc'. If the host
2207  * controller will not enter authentication mode, then the request fails
2208  * (DM_SM_INIT_CFM has a negative response). If the host controller
2209  * does enter authentication mode, then the request succeeds. Note that the
2210  * requested encryption level may not be supported - in this case the
2211  * request still succeeds and the actual encryption level is returned in
2212  * DM_SM_INIT_CFM.
2213  *
2214  * In mode 4, security is service-based, like in mode 2. Secure simple
2215  * pairing is turned on in mode 4 and we now do authorisation before
2216  * authentication. A device must be put into mode 4 to be V2.1 compliant
2217  * Once in mode 4, you cannot change to any other mode.
2218  *
2219  * Sets the default security level to be applied in security modes 2, 3
2220  * and 4 in cases where a service has not been registered with the
2221  * Security Manager. The "default" default security level is defined by
2222  * SECL_DEFAULT, and using this primitive overrides SECL_DEFAULT.
2223  *
2224  * write_auth_enable
2225  * This controls when the security manager issues WRITE_AUTH_ENABLE
2226  * to do mode3-style pairing with legacy devices.
2227  * See DM_SM_BONDING_REQ for a description of this parameter.
2228  *
2229  * config
2230  * This is a bitfield for general config.
2231  *
2232  * bit 0 - Reserved. Shall be set to zero.
2233  * bit 1 - Reserved. Shall be set to zero.
2234  * bit 2 - DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_DEBUG_MODE
2235  * This bit should only be set for debugging using traces.
2236  * If set then the security manager will be put into debug mode.
2237  * HCI_WRITE_SIMPLE_PAIRING_DEBUG_MODE will be issued to the
2238  * controller and the security manager will start generating
2239  * link keys with debug type. You can exit debug mode by
2240  * resending this primitive with this bit unset.
2241  *
2242  * bit 3 - DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_LEGACY_AUTO_PAIR_MISSING_LINK_KEY
2243  * If set then the security manager will automatically start
2244  * pairing if authentication of a legacy device fails with
2245  * 'missing link key'.
2246  *
2247  * bit 4 - DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_NEVER_AUTO_ACCEPT
2248  * Setting this bit will allow application to be looped in while
2249  * pairing.
2250  * If set then the device manager will always issue a
2251  * DM_SM_USER_CONFIRMATION_REQUEST_IND primitive instead of
2252  * auto-accepting, irrespective of the local IO capabilities or
2253  * the authentication requirements of either device.
2254  *
2255  * bit 5 - DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_ALWAYS_TRY_MITM
2256  * Setting this bit is not recommended and should not be necessary.
2257  * If set then the local device will always request MITM protection
2258  * during pairing. If it isn't possible to generate an authenticated
2259  * link key and the local device would not otherwise have requested
2260  * MITM protection then the local device will not abort pairing and
2261  * will allow the generation of an unauthenticated link key.
2262  *
2263  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2264 
2265  /*
2266  * write_auth_enable (bitfield)
2267  */
2268 
2269 /* Never pair during link setup. Use this if you know that the remote host
2270  * supports SSP and SM4 or if you plan to avoid timeouts some other way
2271  */
2272 #define DM_SM_WAE_NEVER 0x0000
2273 
2274 /* Pair during link setup if an ACL does not exist */

2369 /* Reset Root keys (er and ir) with these macros.
2370 
2371  Root keys are used as a seed to generate local keys that are distributed
2372  to remote devices while bonding. Resetting root key will generate
2373  new er,ir values and it will be sent in SM_INIT_CFM for application to store
2374  them in in a non-volatile area (e.g. PSKEY).
2375  Resetting root keys will make all the existing bonding information invalid */
2376 
2377 #define DM_SM_INIT_ALL_AND_RESET_ROOT_KEYS \
2378  (DM_SM_INIT_ALL & ~DM_SM_INIT_SM_STATE)
2379 #define DM_SM_INIT_ALL_SC_AND_RESET_ROOT_KEYS \
2380  (DM_SM_INIT_ALL_SC & ~DM_SM_INIT_SM_STATE)

2382 #define MAX_ENC_KEY_SIZE_VAL 0x10
2383 #define MIN_ENC_KEY_SIZE_VAL 0x07

2385 #define DEFAULT_ENC_KEY_SIZE_VAL 0x07

2388 {

2392 
2393 typedef struct
2394 {
2395  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_SM_INIT_REQ */
2396 
2397  /* Bitfield of options.
2398 
2399  Just bitwise OR required options together.
2400 
2401  Note: write_auth_enable and mode3_enc are mutually exclusive.
2402  mode3_enc only applies to Security Mode 3. write_auth_enable
2403  applies to Security Modes 2 and 4. The Security Manager will
2404  process the security mode option first (if present) and then
2405  will try to set mode3_enc or write_auth_enable depending on
2406  what security mode it finds itself in and whether the relevant
2407  option has been switched on. It's safe to try to set both.
2408  The Security Manager will just ignore the one that doesn't
2409  apply.
2410 
2411  If sm_key_state(Root keys) are not available with application then
2412  it is required to get unique random numbers generated by Bluestack.
2413  To do so,"DM_SM_INIT_SM_STATE" bit shall not be set in options. It
2414  is likely that application will not have root keys for very first
2415  power cycle of product or when product undergoes factory reset. */
2416 
2417  uint16_t options;
2418 
2419  /* Which security mode to use */
2420  dm_security_mode_t security_mode;
2421 
2422  /* Default security level. */
2423  dm_security_level_t security_level_default;
2424 
2425  /* Configuration flags. */
2426  uint16_t config;
2427 
2428  /* Specify when we issue HCI_WRITE_AUTH_ENABLE - See DM_SM_BONDING_REQ */
2429  uint16_t write_auth_enable;
2430 
2431  /* Encryption level for mode 3. One of:
2432  * HCI_ENC_MODE_OFF
2433  * HCI_ENC_MODE_PT_TO_PT
2434  * HCI_ENC_MODE_PT_TO_PT_AND_BCAST
2435  */
2436  uint8_t mode3_enc;
2437 
2438  /* This records the state of the BLE Security Manager. It contains the
2439  master identity and encryption keys, together with the encryption
2440  key diversifier state.
2441 
2442  When an application boots for the first time, it should not attempt to
2443  set these and DM_SM_INIT_SM_STATE bit in options. The Security Manager will then
2444  generate the keys and initiate the diversifier. It will return these
2445  values to the application in the DM_SM_INIT_CFM_T. The application must
2446  then store these values in a non-volatile area (e.g. PSKEY).
2447 
2448  During some pairing processes, the security manager may send new values
2449  of the diversifier - div - to the application. The application must
2450  update the diversifier in non-volatile memory.
2451 
2452  During subsequent boots, the application must return its stored values
2453  for the keys and diversifier to the Security Manager in DM_SM_INIT_REQ
2454  and set DM_SM_INIT_SM_STATE flag in options.
2455 
2456  Failure to do this will mean that any keys distributed from this
2457  device will be rendered invalid at the next reboot. */
2458  DM_SM_KEY_STATE_T sm_key_state;
2459  uint16_t sm_div_state;
2460  uint32_t sm_sign_counter;
2461 
2462  /* Configurable encryption key size (max/min) values */
2463  uint8_t max_enc_key_size_thres; /* Maximun enc key size threshold param */
2464  uint8_t min_enc_key_size_thres; /* Minimum enc key size threshold param */
2465 } DM_SM_INIT_REQ_T;
2466 
2467 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*

2470  *
2471  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2472 /* Bitfield to indicate success or failure.
2473  0 is success, otherwise set bits indicate any problems that were
2474  encountered. */

2480 #define DM_SM_INIT_FAIL_WRITE_SIMPLE_PAIRING_DEBUG_MODE ((uint16_t)0x0004)
2481 /* HCI_WRITE_AUTH_ENABLE failed. Can't enter/exit Security Mode 3 */

2483 /* HCI_WRITE_ENC_MODE failed. Can't change Security Mode 3 encryption mode */

2485 /* HCI_WRITE_SECURE_CONNECTIONS_HOST_SUPPORT failed. Can't enter Security Mode 4 encryption mode */
2486 #define DM_SM_INIT_FAIL_WRITE_SC_HOST_SUPPORT ((uint16_t)0x0020)

2514 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2515  * PURPOSE
2516  * A request from the Security Manager for a link key required for
2517  * authentication with the specified remote device. The application must
2518  * respond with a DM_SM_LINK_KEY_REQUEST_RSP primitive containing
2519  * the link and type, or with no link key and 'key_type' set to
2520  * DM_SM_KEY_TYPE_NONE to reject the request. 'authenticated' will be
2521  * set to TRUE if an authenticated link key is required.
2522  *
2523  * The Security Manager will only issue a link key request if it does
2524  * not already have a suitable link key for that device in the device
2525  * database.
2526  *
2527  * If an ACL exists then rhsf will provide the first 15 bits of the
2528  * remote host's supported features. Currently only one bit is defined
2529  * (bit 0), which is 1 if the remote host supports SSP and 0 if it
2530  * doesn't (legacy pre-2.1 host). If no ACL exists then we return 0xFFFF.
2531  *
2532  * If this parameter is set to 0 and initiated_outgoing is TRUE then sending
2533  * a negative response will tell the security manager to initiate legacy
2534  * pairing on an existing ACL. This can potentially lead to timeouts on
2535  * some devices. To try to avoid timing out, you may want to prefetch
2536  * the PIN from the user, set up an SDP 'ping' to keep the ACL alive, or
2537  * whatever you did to avoid these problems in SM2.
2538  *
2539  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2540 
2541 /* rhsf parameter */
2542 #define DM_SM_RHSF_NO_ACL 0xFFFF
2543 #define DM_SM_RHSF_NONE 0x0000
2544 #define DM_SM_RHSF_SSP 0x0001
2545 
2546 typedef struct
2547 {
2548  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_LINK_KEY_REQUEST_IND */
2549  phandle_t phandle; /* Destination phandle */
2550  BD_ADDR_T bd_addr; /* address of remote device */
2551 
2552  /* Class of device for peer, valid for incoming connections only else 0 */
2553  uint24_t dev_class;
2554 
2555  bool_t authenticated; /* TRUE if we need authenticated key */
2556  /* TRUE if this is security for an outgoing connection that we've initiated */
2557  bool_t initiated_outgoing;
2558  uint16_t rhsf; /* Remote host's supported features */
2559 } DM_SM_LINK_KEY_REQUEST_IND_T;
2560 
2561 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2562  * PURPOSE
2563  * A response to DM_SM_LINK_KEY_REQUEST_RES
2564  *
2565  * To respond with a suitable link key, set 'key_type' according to
2566  * 'HCI Link Key Notification Event Key Type', in hci.h, and then put
2567  * the link key at the end of the primitive as normal.
2568  *
2569  * To reject the request, set 'key_type' to DM_SM_KEY_TYPE_NONE and
2570  * add nothing to the end of the primitive.
2571  *
2572  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2573 
2574 /* key_type */
2575 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_NONE ((uint8_t) 0xFE)
2576 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_LEGACY HCI_COMBINATION_KEY
2577 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_DEBUG HCI_DEBUG_COMBINATION_KEY
2578 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_UNAUTHENTICATED_P192 HCI_UNAUTHENTICATED_COMBINATION_KEY_P192
2579 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_AUTHENTICATED_P192 HCI_AUTHENTICATED_COMBINATION_KEY_P192
2580 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_CHANGED HCI_CHANGED_COMBINATION_KEY
2581 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_UNAUTHENTICATED_P256 HCI_UNAUTHENTICATED_COMBINATION_KEY_P256
2582 #define DM_SM_LINK_KEY_AUTHENTICATED_P256 HCI_AUTHENTICATED_COMBINATION_KEY_P256
2583

2585 {

2588  BD_ADDR_T bd_addr; /* Remote device address */
2589 
2590  /* See HCI Link Key Notification Event Key Type in hci.h */
2591  uint8_t key_type;
2592 
2593  uint8_t *key;
2594 } DM_SM_LINK_KEY_REQUEST_RSP_T;

2688 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2689  * PURPOSE
2690  * Authorisation response from the application to the Security Manager.
2691  *
2692  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2693 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_BIT 0 /* Set to authorise connection */
2694 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_TWICE_BIT 1 /* Set to apply to next connection as well (within life of ACL) */
2695 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_LIFE_OF_ACL_BIT 2 /* Set to apply to all connections for life of ACL */
2696 
2697 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_REJECT_ONCE 0x0000
2698 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_ONCE (1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_BIT)
2699 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_REJECT_TWICE (1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_TWICE_BIT)
2700 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_TWICE \
2701  ((1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_BIT) | (1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_TWICE_BIT))
2702 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_REJECT_LIFE_OF_ACL \
2703  (1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_LIFE_OF_ACL_BIT)
2704 #define DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_LIFE_OF_ACL \
2705  ((1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_ACCEPT_BIT) | (1 << DM_SM_AUTHORISE_LIFE_OF_ACL_BIT))
2706

2887 
2888 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2889  * DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_IND
2890  *
2891  * The Security Manager asks the application for IO capability information
2892  *
2893  * authentication_requirements is present so that the application can
2894  * request General Bonding during service-based security and so that
2895  * the application can insist on MITM protection, overriding the
2896  * security manager. Effectively, the application can upgrade the security
2897  * requirements. Setting authentication_requirements for dedicated bonding
2898  * will always be ignored by the security manager as this will only be done
2899  * when you issue a DM_SM_BONDING_REQ or when you are the responder and the
2900  * initiator has set its authentication_requirements for dedicated bonding.
2901  *
2902  * For BLE security, the authentication_requirements field should be set
2903  * using the DM_SM_SECURITY_ defines. See DM_SM_SECURITY_REQ.
2904  *
2905  * Notes for BR/EDR:
2906  * 1. An Application cannot downgrade the security requirements. If the
2907  * security manager believes that MITM protection is required then
2908  * it will request an authenticated link key, irrespective of the
2909  * authentication_requirements set in this primitive.
2910  *
2911  * 2. If you are doing dedicated bonding then the security manager will
2912  * send appropriate authentication_requirements (i.e. it will send either
2913  * HCI_MITM_NOT_REQUIRED_DEDICATED_BONDING or
2914  * HCI_MITM_REQUIRED_DEDICATED_BONDING) to the remote device.
2915  *
2916  * 3. If you are doing service-based security then the security manager
2917  * will send appropriate authentication_requirements (i.e. it will send
2918  * HCI_MITM_NOT_REQUIRED_NO_BONDING, HCI_MITM_REQUIRED_NO_BONDING,
2919  * HCI_MITM_NOT_REQUIRED_GENERAL_BONDING or
2920  * HCI_MITM_REQUIRED_GENERAL_BONDING) to the remote device.
2921  *
2922  * 4. You should be careful about upgrading the security requirements
2923  * to MITM protection required. It is probably only worth doing if
2924  * you know that MITM protection is going to be required anyway. This
2925  * might be the case when you are opening the RFCOMM MUX (which might
2926  * not require MITM protection) in order to open an RFCOMM channel
2927  * that does require MITM protection. You might be able to save some
2928  * time by upgrading to MITM_REQUIRED when opening the MUX as this
2929  * will avoid pairing twice.
2930  *
2931  * 5. Remember that if you insist on MITM protection and the
2932  * io_capabilities of the two devices prevent the creation of
2933  * an authenticated link key then pairing will fail.
2934  *
2935  * If oob_data_present == 0 then both oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r shall be
2936  * NULL and there shall be no associated data with the primitive.
2937  *
2938  * For BR/EDR, if oob_data_present == 1 then oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r
2939  * shall each point to SIZE_OOB_DATA words of OOB data. If you only have
2940  * oob_hash_c then zero the oob_rand_r data.
2941  *
2942  * For BLE, if oob_data_present == 2 then oob_hash_c shall point to
2943  * SIZE_OOB_DATA words of OOB data. oob_rand_r shall be NULL.
2944  *
2945  * For BLE SC, if oob_data_present == 1 then oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r
2946  * shall each point to series of OOB hash and Rand based on the bits set
2947  * from DM_SM_OOB_DATA_P256 and DM_SM_OOB_DATA_P192
2948  * oob_hash_c = hash_xx|hash_yy
2949  * oob_rand_r = rand_xx|rand_yy
2950  *
2951  * Cross transport key derivation (Single pairing): This procedure can be done
2952  * in two different ways,
2953  *
2954  * 1. LE SC key derivation and distribution over BR/EDR transport after
2955  * successful BR/EDR SC pairing.
2956  * Bluestack in a master role on BR/EDR transport by itself will decide
2957  * whether to initiate single pairing procedure or not after successful
2958  * BR/EDR SC pairing. LE SC key derivation and distribution will be
2959  * automatically initiated by sending iocap request to the application
2960  * with DM_SM_FLAGS_SMP_OVER_BREDR flag set. Application may choose to
2961  * reject single pairing procedure by replying with
2962  * DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_NEG_RSP
2963  * Once application replies to iocap request positively, Bluestack will try
2964  * to derive and distribute LE keys on BR/EDR transport. If procedure is
2965  * successful then DM_SM_KEYS_IND event is sent to the application.
2966  * Upon completion of this procedure,status will be indicated to the
2967  * applications by sending DM_SM_SIMPLE_PAIRING_COMPLETE_IND event with
2968  * DM_SM_FLAGS_SMP_OVER_BREDR flag set.
2969  *
2970  * 2. Link key derivation from LTK during LESC pairing.
2971  * Bluestack will own up setting or resetting of 'link key' bit during
2972  * LESC pairing. Later,if a link key is derived successfully then it will be
2973  * sent to the application in a separate DM_SM_KEYS_IND event before LESC
2974  * pairing procedure is concluded with DM_SM_SIMPLE_PAIRING_COMPLETE_IND .
2975  *
2976  * NOTE:
2977  * 1. If Application wants Bluestack to disable Cross Transport Keys Derivation
2978  * then it may set DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_DISABLE_CTKD in DM_SM_INIT_REQ.
2979  *
2980  * 2. If an application wants Bluestack to selectively generate Cross Transport
2981  * Keys then it needs to set DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_SELECTIVE_CTKD in
2982  * DM_SM_INIT_REQ. At the same time it needs to make sure that bit
2983  * DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_DISABLE_CTKD is NOT set .
2984  * Refer DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND_T prim for more details
2985  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2986 typedef DM_COMMON_IND_T DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_IND_T;
2987 
2988 
2989 /*
2990  * OOB data can be P192 and/or P256 and so the following interface
2991  * needs to populate the oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r carefully
2992  * Hash to be populated in the following order if both the bits (for 192 and
2993  * 256)are set:
2994  * MSB-hash256|hash192-LSB...
2995  * MSB-rand256|rand192-LSB...
2996  * In case only one of them is being conveyed (P256) then we can just send
2997  * MSB-hash256-LSB...
2998  * MSB-rand256-LSB...
2999  */
3000 
3001 /*
3002  * oob_data_present is a bit field and shall be used as below
3003  */
3004 
3005 /* Possible values for oob_data_present */
3006 #define DM_SM_OOB_DATA_NONE 0x00 /* No OOB data */
3007 
3008 /*
3009  * For P192 on LE transport, only oob_hash_c shall be supplied
3010  * For P192 on BREDR transport, both oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r shall be supplied
3011  * For P256 on either transport, both oob_hash_c and oob_rand_r shall be supplied
3012  */
3013 #define DM_SM_OOB_DATA_P192 0x01 /* P192 OOB Data Present */
3014 #define DM_SM_OOB_DATA_P256 0x02 /* Both hash_c and Rand_r is present */
3015 
3016 /*
3017  * Flag indicating that applications are flexible on their MITM requirements.
3018  * This would be sent as a part of io_capability and
3019  * can be set using the macros define below
3020  */
3021 #define DM_SM_MITM_FLEXIBLE 0x80
3022 
3023 /*
3024  * Macro for application to add or clear MITM flexibility.
3025  * The user of these macros shall provide pointer to the primitive
3026  */
3027 #define DM_SM_SET_MITM_FLEXIBLE(pIOCapsReqRsp) \
3028  pIOCapsReqRsp->io_capability |= DM_SM_MITM_FLEXIBLE;
3029 #define DM_SM_CLEAR_MITM_FLEXIBLE(pIOCapsReqRsp) \
3030  pIOCapsReqRsp->io_capability &= (~DM_SM_MITM_FLEXIBLE);
3031 /*
3032  * When the device has been configured in SC ONLY mode, following parameters
3033  * will have the default values irrespective of what Application provides

3035  * - SC bit would be set in authentication_requirements
3036  * - MITM flexibility bit in io_capability would be reset

3040 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
3041  * DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP
3042  * This primitive is used to respond to initiation of pairing process both on
3043  * LE and BR/EDR transports.
3044  * Apart from guideline provided in DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_IND for pairing,
3045  * API usage is explained here.
3046  *
3047  * io_capability : Apart from IO capabilities from specification,this field's
3048  * MSB is utilized to indicate application flexibility on MITM requirement when
3049  * MITM flag is set in authentication_requirements field. At present,
3050  * MITM flexibility is supported only for LE.
3051  *
3052  * oob_data_present, oob_hash_c, oob_rand_r : Refer OOB related macros
3053  * explained above.
3054  *
3055  * authentication_requirements : bit mask used to request authentication
3056  * requirements of the user. Bit positions are used as explained in SMP
3057  * specification Ref : Core 4.2,Vol 3,Part H,Sec 3.5.1 and 3.5.2.
3058  * Note : LE Secure Connection aware applications should always set SC bit in
3059  * this API.
3060  *
3061  * key_distribution : bit mask used to specifies keys to be exchanged with
3062  * remote device during LE pairing. DM_SM_KEY_DIST_* set of macros are defined
3063  * to help user to select initiator and responder key distribution.
3064  * Note :
3065  * A) LE Secure Connection aware applications shall always set both
3066  * initiator and responder Encryption key bit to 1.
3067  * B) In case application uses resolvable private address, it is mandated for
3068  * the application to set the initiator & responder indentity bits to 1.
3069  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3070 typedef struct
3071 {
3072  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP */
3073  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt;
3074  uint8_t io_capability;
3075  uint8_t oob_data_present;
3076  uint8_t authentication_requirements;
3077  uint8_t *oob_hash_c;
3078  uint8_t *oob_rand_r;
3079  uint16_t key_distribution; /* SMP only */
3080 } DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP_T;
3081

3097 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
3098  * DM_SM_USER_CONFIRMATION_REQUEST_IND
3099  *
3100  * This primitive is sent when the numeric comparison authentication model
3101  * is being used for pairing and provides the application with the generated
3102  * numeric value.
3103  *
3104  * If io_cap_local indicates that the local device is capable of displaying
3105  * the numeric value then the application shall display it until
3106  * DM_SM_SIMPLE_PAIRING_COMPLETE_IND is received.
3107  *
3108  * io_cap_remote is there for information only and indicates whether or
3109  * not a correctly implemented remote device will be displaying the number.
3110  *
3111  * flags is a bitfield defined above. See DM_COMMON_IND.
3112  * If DM_SM_FLAGS_INITIATOR is set then this pairing has been initiated by
3113  * the local device. If DM_SM_FLAGS_RESPONSE_REQUIRED is set then the
3114  * application shall respond with either DM_SM_USER_CONFIRMATION_REQUEST_RSP
3115  * or DM_SM_USER_CONFIRMATION_REQUEST_NEG_RSP. If
3116  * DM_SM_FLAGS_RESPONSE_REQUIRED is not set then the application shall not
3117  * respond (but shall still display the numeric value if io_cap_local
3118  * indicates that it shall).
3119  *
3120  * Note:
3121  * If either device (local/remote) has IO capability as NoInputNoOutput then
3122  * the numeric value is insignificant. So application shall ignore and also
3123  * not display it.
3124  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

3126 {

3128  phandle_t phandle; /* Destination phandle */
3129  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt;
3130 
3131  /* Class of device for peer, valid for incoming connections only else 0 */
3132  uint24_t dev_class;
3133 
3134  uint32_t numeric_value; /* Value to compare */
3135  uint8_t io_cap_local; /* Effective IO capabilities of local device. */
3136  uint8_t io_cap_remote; /* Effective IO capabilities of remote device. */
3137  uint16_t flags; /* See DM_COMMON_IND_T */
3138 } DM_SM_USER_CONFIRMATION_REQUEST_IND_T;

3370 #define SM_ERROR_BASE 0xC0
3371 
3372 /*
3373  * Internal error codes used in Security Manager Protocol between Bluestack
3374  * and application.
3375  * Range reserved is 0xA0 to 0xBF (32 possible error codes) since error codes
3376  * for Security Manager Protol start from 0xC0 onwards.
3377  */
3378 #define SM_INTERNAL_ERROR_BASE 0xA0
3379 #define SM_INT_ERR_ENCRYPTION_REFRESH_FAILED (SM_INTERNAL_ERROR_BASE+1)
3380 /*
3381  * Once the application receives mentioned error code for pairing failed
3382  * it would mean that next attempt on pairing on the current link shall lead
3383  * to the disconnecttion of the link.
3384  * Suggested way is that application wraps up any other ongoing activity on the
3385  * current link and then bring down this link before trying to pair with the
3386  * same device.
3387  */
3388 #define SM_INT_ERR_SMP_PDU_TIMEOUT (SM_INTERNAL_ERROR_BASE+2)

3397  when sm_error is a constant */

3450 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
3451  * DM_SM_BONDING_REQ/CFM
3452  *
3453  * The application requests bonding with a remote device. First we delete
3454  * any link key we have in the device database.
3455  *
3456  * If the remote device is in SM4 then we make sure an ACL exists before
3457  * authenticating it.
3458  *
3459  * If the remote device is legacy then the write_auth_enable parameter
3460  * determines in what circumstances we try to pair during link setup
3461  * (just like mode 3).
3462  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3463 typedef struct
3464 {
3465  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_BONDING_REQ */
3466  TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt; /* Remote device address */
3467  uint16_t flags; /* Reserved and shall be set to 0 */
3468 } DM_SM_BONDING_REQ_T;
3469 
3470 typedef struct
3471 {
3472  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_BONDING_CFM */
3473  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
3474  TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt; /* Remote device address */
3475  uint16_t flags; /* See DM_COMMON_IND_T */
3476  hci_error_t status;
3477 } DM_SM_BONDING_CFM_T;
3478 
3479 /* The status field in DM_SM_BONDING_CFM_T returns a standard HCI error code,
3480  or one of the following two additional error codes. */
3481 #define DM_SM_BONDING_CANCELLED ((hci_error_t)0xFF)
3482 /* DM_SM_BONDING_NO_PAIRING is generated when we cannot prevent the baseband
3483  from automatically authenticating an existing link key. This will only occur
3484  for legacy security modes, i.e., it will never happen in Security Mode 4.
3485  To avoid this error, close the ACL before bonding. */
3486 #define DM_SM_BONDING_NO_PAIRING ((hci_error_t)0xFE)
3487 
3488 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
3489  * DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ
3490  *
3491  * The application requests that a previous DM_SM_BONDING_REQ be cancelled.
3492  *
3493  * This is not guaranteed to work but it stands a better chance of working
3494  * the earlier it is used.
3495  *
3496  * If the DM_SM_BONDING_REQ request is still queued then the security
3497  * manager will just remove it. If the ACL manager is currently trying to
3498  * connect an ACL for bonding, then the security manager will try to
3499  * cancel this. If the ACL is already up and the pairing process has started
3500  * then the security manager will issue negative replies to halt it as
3501  * soon as possible. If you set force = TRUE then, if all else fails,
3502  * the DM will cancel bonding by bringing down the ACL, even if there are
3503  * l2cap connections open.
3504  *
3505  * There is no DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_CFM, but if cancellation was successful
3506  * then the DM_SM_BONDING_CFM associated with the original bonding request
3507  * will return with status = DM_SM_BONDING_CANCELLED. If it was too late to
3508  * cancel bonding and pairing has already succeeded, DM_SM_BONDING_CFM will
3509  * return with status = DM_SM_BONDING_SUCCESS and it is then up to the
3510  * application to unbond the device.
3511  *
3512  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3513 typedef struct
3514 {
3515  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ */
3516  TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt; /* Remote device address */
3517  uint16_t flags; /* See DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ */
3518 } DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ_T;

3608 #define DM_SM_MAX_NUM_KEYS 5
3609 #define DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS 3
3610 #define DM_SM_KEY_MASK 0x0007
3611 #define DM_SM_KEYS_EXISTING 0x8000
3612 #define DM_SM_KEYS_UPDATE_EXISTING DM_SM_KEYS_EXISTING
3613 #define DM_SM_KEYS_REPLACE_EXISTING 0x0000
3614 #define DM_SM_DIV_LTK 0x4000
3615 #define DM_SM_DIV_CSRK 0x8000
3616 #define DM_SM_DIV_TYPE_MASK (DM_SM_DIV_LTK|DM_SM_DIV_CSRK)

3618 /*
3619  * While using this macro, keys - one, two, three, four and five should
3620  have values from enum DM_SM_KEY_TYPE_T.
3621  Field update_or_replace should be either DM_SM_KEYS_UPDATE_EXISTING or
3622  DM_SM_KEYS_REPLACE_EXISTING.
3623  */
3624 #define DM_SM_KEYS_PRESENT(one, two, three, four, five, update_or_replace) \
3625  ((((one) & DM_SM_KEY_MASK) << (DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS * 0)) | \
3626  (((two) & DM_SM_KEY_MASK) << (DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS * 1)) | \
3627  (((three) & DM_SM_KEY_MASK) << (DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS * 2)) | \
3628  (((four) & DM_SM_KEY_MASK) << (DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS * 3)) | \
3629  (((five) & DM_SM_KEY_MASK) << (DM_SM_NUM_KEY_BITS * 4)) | \
3630  (update_or_replace))

3644  Therefore, this parameter is meaningful only when LE related keys
3645  are present.
3646  */
3647  uint16_t security_requirements;
3648 
3649  /* The number of significant octets in the LTK */
3650  uint16_t encryption_key_size;

3658  uint16_t present;

3679  (zeroed if not present) */

3681 
3682 /* Security requirements bitfield definitions
3683 
3684  DM_SM_SECURITY_BONDING - In Bluetooth Low Energy, devices bond by
3685  exchaning keys after the link has been encrypted. If the devices are
3686  not bonding then no key distribution should take place. Note that
3687  key distribution is determined by the key_distribution field in the
3688  DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP primitive. (That field should be set
3689  to zero by any device that does not want to bond.)
3690 
3691  DM_SM_SECURITY_REFRESH_ENCRYPTION - This bit is used to enforce refresh of
3692  encryption on an already encrypted link.
3693  Note: Refresh encryption bit should be set only when LTK is available
3694  with the local device.
3695 
3696  DM_SM_SECURITY_ENCRYPTION - This bit specifies a requirement for an
3697  encrypted link. If there is no Out of Band data available then the
3698  security manager will default to using the Just Works pairing method
3699  and will produce an unauthenticated key with no MITM protection.
3700  Note: As per the table (below), this bit is in-significant and hence
3701  don't-care.
3702 
3703  DM_SM_SECURITY_MITM_PROTECTION - This bit specifies a requirement for
3704  MITM protection. If there is no Out of Band data available then the
3705  security manager will try to use passkey pairing. If the IO capabilities
3706  of the two devices do not allow this then the pairing will fail.
3707 
3708  DM_SM_SECURITY_QUERY_ONLY - This bit determines the security manager's
3709  behaviour upon finding that the current state of the link does not
3710  provide the security requested. If this bit is set then the secruity
3711  manager will simply report back failure. If it is not set then the
3712  security manager will initiate pairing to increase the security level.
3713  This bit is intended to be set only by ATT, which will need to query
3714  the current security level. The application will want to increase the
3715  security level to match its request and so should not set this bit.
3716 
3717  If requested security requirements are lesser or equal to
3718  the link's current security level
3719  Then
3720  Following table defines the action taken when authentication
3721  requirements corresponds to all possible combinations of
3722  - DM_SM_SECURITY_ENCRYPTION &
3723  - DM_SM_SECURITY_REFRESH_ENCRYPTION
3724  and the link's current status.
3725  Else
3726  Trigger pairing process.
3727 
3728  |------------------------------------------------------------------|
3729  | Encrypt | Encrypt Refresh | Link's current status |
3730  | Request | Request |--------------------------------|
3731  | | | Un-encrypted | Encrypted |
3732  | | |--------------------------------|
3733  | | | Action taken |
3734  |-----------|---------------------|----------------|---------------|
3735  | X | 0 | Encrypt | Do Nothing, |
3736  | | | | Send Confm. |
3737  | | | | SUCCESS |
3738  | | | | |
3739  | X | 1 | Encrypt | Refresh |
3740  | | | | |
3741  |------------------------------------------------------------------|
3742 
3743  Note : If pairing was triggered as a result of DM_SM_SECURITY_REQ API call
3744  then application shall set same security (auth) requirement set in
3745  DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP.
3746 */
3747 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_BONDING 0x0001 /* Create a bond */
3748 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_MITM_PROTECTION 0x0004 /* Protect against MITM */
3749 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_SECURE_CONNECTIONS 0x0008 /* Enable secure connections */
3750 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_REFRESH_ENCRYPTION 0x1000 /* Enforce encryption refresh
3751  on an encrypted link */
3752 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_ENCRYPTION 0x4000 /* As per the above table,
3753  this bit is in-significant
3754  and hence don't-care */
3755 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_QUERY_ONLY 0x8000 /* Query current state */
3756 
3757 /*
3758  * Bluestack would set this in case H6 was used while deriving the
3759  * cross transport keys in the DM_SM_KEYS_IND_T event only.
3760  * Application shall use this to confirm on its usage for various services.
3761  */
3762 /* LE keys were derived using H6 */
3763 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_LE_H6_SET 0x0100
3764 /* BREDR key was derived using H6 */
3765 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_BREDR_H6_SET 0x0200
3766 
3767 
3768 #define DM_SM_LE_ENCRYPTION 0x01
3769 #define DM_SM_LE_MITM 0x02
3770 #define DM_SM_LE_SIGNING 0x04
3771 #define DM_SM_LE_SC_ENCRYPTION 0x08
3772 
3773 
3774 /* Security levels derived from bitfield definitions above */
3775 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_NONE 0x0000
3776 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING \
3777  (DM_SM_SECURITY_ENCRYPTION)
3778 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_BONDING \
3779  (DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_BONDING)
3780 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING \
3781  (DM_SM_SECURITY_ENCRYPTION | DM_SM_SECURITY_MITM_PROTECTION)
3782 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_BONDING \
3783  (DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_BONDING)
3784 
3785 /* Requesting Security levels for SC */
3786 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING_SC \
3787  (DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_SECURE_CONNECTIONS)
3788 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_BONDING_SC \
3789  (DM_SM_SECURITY_UNAUTHENTICATED_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_SECURE_CONNECTIONS)
3790 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING_SC \
3791  (DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_NO_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_SECURE_CONNECTIONS)
3792 #define DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_BONDING_SC \
3793  (DM_SM_SECURITY_AUTHENTICATED_BONDING | DM_SM_SECURITY_SECURE_CONNECTIONS)
3794

3906  associated with this remote device.

3997 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
3998  * PURPOSE
3999  * This API generates a random address of type requested and then sets
4000  * the value to controller. The newly generated address and TGAP timer
4001  * shall be effective on subsequent scan/adv. There after the random
4002  * address would keep changing at least by TGAP timer time frame.
4003  *
4004  * In case static address is provided by application, it sets the same
4005  * static random address to controller if valid, otherwise a new static
4006  * address is generated and set with controller. TGAP timer is
4007  * not applicable when local address set is static.
4008  *
4009  * Note:
4010  * TGAP(private_addr_int) timer shall be implemented below this interface.
4011  * The random address generated upon timer expiry is not indicated to the
4012  * application.
4013  * In case the application requires the local address configured,it can
4014  * send DM_SM_READ_RANDOM_ADDRESS_REQ to read the current local
4015  * configured address.
4016  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4017 typedef struct
4018 {
4019  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_AUTO_CONFIGURE_LOCAL_ADDRESS_REQ */
4020  DM_SM_RANDOM_ADDRESS_T set_random_addr_type; /* random address type */
4021  TP_BD_ADDR_T static_addrt; /* Static address from application,
4022  Transport type would always be LE */
4023  uint16_t rpa_timeout; /* TGAP or rpa timeout in seconds */
4024 } DM_SM_AUTO_CONFIGURE_LOCAL_ADDRESS_REQ_T;

4125 /*-----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
4126  * PURPOSE
4127  * The Security Manager asks the application to allow Bluestack to
4128  * selectively generate Cross Transport Keys for the indicated
4129  * address.
4130  *
4131  * Application may want Bluestack to selectively derive Cross Transport
4132  * Keys with remote device. In that case it may override the default
4133  * behaviour of Bluestack for generating Cross Transport keys by setting
4134  * config bit DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_SELECTIVE_CTKD in DM_SM_INIT_REQ.
4135  *
4136  * Once set, DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND shall be sent to
4137  * application. Its response "DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_RSP"
4138  * would allow Bluestack to proceed/skip with Cross Transport Keys
4139  * Derivation on given transport with indicated address.
4140  *
4141  * NOTE:
4142  * 1) Setting DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_SELECTIVE_CTKD bit in DM_SM_INIT_REQ
4143  * shall enable DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND/
4144  * DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_RSP interface API
4145  * with application. This indication may come if Cross Transport Key
4146  * derivation with the remote device is possible.
4147  *
4148  * 2) Application NOT setting DM_SM_SEC_MODE_CONFIG_SELECTIVE_CTKD bit in
4149  * DM_SM_INIT_REQ shall allow default behaviour of Bluestack generating
4150  * Cross Transport Keys as mentioned in DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_IND
4151  *
4152  * 3) In remote initiated pairing procedure application may receive
4153  * DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND and
4154  * DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_IND concurrently. It is advised to respond
4155  * to DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND immediately AND before
4156  * DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP. Remote device may choose to skip CTKD
4157  * if the response is delayed or DM_SM_IO_CAPABILITY_REQUEST_RSP is sent
4158  * beforehand.
4159  *-----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4160 typedef struct
4161 {
4162  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND_T */
4163  phandle_t phandle; /* Destination phandle */
4164  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt; /* Remote device's address. The indicated
4165  transport in the request is where the
4166  pairing is being done. The CTKD procedure
4167  would happen to derive the keys of the
4168  other transport.*/
4169  uint8_t identifier; /* Unique identifier value the application must copy
4170  into DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_RSP
4171  when responding to this message on BREDR transport.
4172  On LE transport identifier is reserved*/
4173  uint16_t flags; /* reserved */
4174 } DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND_T;
4175 
4176 /* The flags below can be set in DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_RSP
4177  * to enable or disable Cross transport key derivation.
4178  */
4179 #define DM_SM_FLAG_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_DISABLE 0x0000
4180 #define DM_SM_FLAG_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_ENABLE 0x0001
4181 
4182 /*-----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
4183  * PURPOSE
4184  * This primitive is used to respond to

4186  *
4187  * If the application wants Bluestack to generate Cross Transport Keys then
4188  * it shall set flag DM_SM_FLAG_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_ENABLE in the
4189  * DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_RSP for
4190  * DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND it recieved with indicated
4191  * device
4192  *
4193  * If the application sets DM_SM_FLAG_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_DISABLE flag
4194  * then Bluestack will not generate Cross Transport Keys for other transport
4195  *-----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4196 typedef struct

4201  DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_IND */

4203 } DM_SM_GENERATE_CROSS_TRANS_KEY_REQUEST_RSP_T;

4274 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
4275  * PURPOSE
4276  * Request from Application task for the DM to create an ACL to the
4277  * specified remote device. This might be used for pairing, for example.
4278  * The DM allows both L2CAP and the application to request ACLs.
4279  * The DM keeps track of who has an interest in
4280  * each ACL, and will only disconnect the ACL when all interested parties
4281  * have released the ACL (by DM_ACL_DISCONNECT_REQ and DM_ACL_CLOSE_REQ).
4282  *
4283  * DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ registers the application's interest in the ACL. DM will
4284  * create the link if it does not already exist. DM will always respond
4285  * with DM_ACL_OPEN_CFM, indicating success or failure. If successful, the
4286  * application may subsequently call DM_ACL_CLOSE_REQ to relinquish its
4287  * interest in the ACL - DM will then release the link if L2CAP is not
4288  * using it.
4289  *
4290  * The DM keeps the application informed of the state of all ACLs via the
4291  * DM_ACL_OPENED_IND and DM_ACL_CLOSED_IND primitives. Note that there is
4292  * no specific response to DM_ACL_CLOSE_REQ, as the DM_ACL_CLOSED_IND is
4293  * only issued when all users of the ACL have released it.
4294  *
4295  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4296 
4297 /* Bitfield of options
4298 
4299  Bit 0 DM_ACL_FLAG_INCOMING
4300  Will be set in DM_ACL_OPENED_IND and DM_ACL_CLOSED_IND primitives
4301  if the ACL was created by the remote device. It shall be set to
4302  0 in DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ, DM_ACL_CLOSE_REQ, DM_SM_BONDING_REQ and
4303  DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ.
4304 
4305  Bit 1 DM_ACL_FLAG_ALL
4306  Indicates that request should apply to all connections. If this
4307  is set then any Bluetooth address in the primitives will be
4308  ignored. This shall be set to 0 in DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ,
4309  DM_SM_BONDING_REQ and DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ and will be
4310  set to 0 in DM_ACL_OPENED_IND and DM_ACL_CLOSED_IND.
4311 
4312  Bit 2 DM_ACL_FLAG_FORCE
4313  Indicates that a more aggressive version of the command should
4314  be used. This shall be set to 0 in DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ,
4315  DM_SM_BONDING_REQ and will be set to 0 in DM_ACL_OPENED_IND and
4316  DM_ACL_CLOSED_IND. If set in DM_ACL_CLOSE_REQ then the ACL will
4317  be disconnected irrespective of any L2CAP connections that are
4318  active. If set in DM_SM_BONDING_CANCEL_REQ then, if all else
4319  fails, the device manager will cancel bonding by bringing down
4320  the ACL, even if there are active L2CAP connections.
4321 
4322  Bit 3 DM_ACL_FLAG_ULP
4323  Indicates that request shall be set for BLE connection and
4324  Will be set in upstream primitives for BLE connection.
4325 
4326  Bit 4 DM_ACL_FLAG_ULP_RRPA_RESOLVED
4327  Significant to DM_ACL_OPENED_IND for LE transport only on OFFCHIP
4328  implementation.
4329  If set, then it implies that peer's resolvable random private
4330  address (RRPA) is resolved based on the keys added to SM device
4331  database by application.
4332  In ONCHIP its always set to 0.
4333 
4334  Bits 5-15 Reserved
4335  Shall be set to 0.
4336 */
4337 #define DM_ACL_FLAG_INCOMING 0x0001
4338 #define DM_ACL_FLAG_ALL 0x0002
4339 #define DM_ACL_FLAG_FORCE 0x0004
4340 #define DM_ACL_FLAG_ULP 0x0008
4341 #define DM_ACL_FLAG_ULP_RRPA_RESOLVED 0x0010
4342 
4343 typedef struct
4344 {
4345  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ */
4346  TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt; /* Remote device address */
4347  uint16_t flags; /* Bitfield of options */
4348 } DM_ACL_OPEN_REQ_T;
4349

4356 typedef struct

4532 /* DM tells AMPM about need for physical connection. This happens after
4533  l2cap receives a connect request from a higher layer and after the ACL
4534  is up and encryption has been enabled, but before any l2cap connection
4535  signalling. On the initiating side, the AMPM will receive one of these
4536  for every l2cap channel to be connected, irrespective of whether or not
4537  the required physical connection exists. This is not sent on the responding
4538  side as by the time the responder knows about the l2cap connection, the
4539  physical channel is already connected.
4540 
4541  AMPM DM
4542  DM_AMPM_CONNECT_IND
4543  <---------------------------------------------
4544  DM_AMPM_CONNECT_RSP
4545  --------------------------------------------->
4546 */

4552  l2ca_cid_t cid;
4553  l2ca_controller_t local_amp_id;
4554  l2ca_controller_t remote_amp_id;
4555 } DM_AMPM_CONNECT_IND_T;

5255 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5256  * PURPOSE
5257  * Defines the powerstate(s) to be applied to the specified ACL. It
5258  * takes the form of a list of successive power modes which the ACL moves
5259  * through over periods of increasing inactivity. If at anytime there
5260  * is activity on the ACL, control will reset to the first powerstate.
5261  *
5262  * Each powerstate is defined using the LP_POWERSTATE_T structure.
5263  * The 'mode' entry is used to define the Bluetooth power mode.
5264  * The 'min_interval' etc fields define the parameters of the Bluetooth
5265  * power mode - see the HCI spec.
5266  * The 'duration' is the length of time, in seconds, that the ACL will
5267  * remain in this state. When this period expires, control moves
5268  * to the next state. The last powerstate therefore MUST have an
5269  * infinite duration (zero).
5270  *
5271  * Notes
5272  * It is important for the application to know the remote supported
5273  * features before populating the power table. It would make no sense to
5274  * ask for low power modes those are not supported.
5275  * Refer: DM_HCI_READ_REMOTE_SUPP_FEATURES_REQ_T
5276  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5277 typedef uint8_t lp_powermode_t;
5278 #define LP_POWERMODE_ACTIVE ((lp_powermode_t)0x00)
5279 #define LP_POWERMODE_SNIFF ((lp_powermode_t)0x01)
5280 /* Passive mode is a "don't care" setting where the local device will not
5281  attempt to alter the power mode. */
5282 #define LP_POWERMODE_PASSIVE ((lp_powermode_t)0xff)
5283 
5284 typedef struct
5285 {
5286  lp_powermode_t mode;
5287  uint16_t min_interval;
5288  uint16_t max_interval;
5289  uint16_t attempt;
5290  uint16_t timeout;
5291  uint16_t duration; /* time to spend in this mode */
5292 } LP_POWERSTATE_T;/* autogen_makefile_ignore_this (DO NOT REMOVE THIS COMMENT) */
5293 
5294 typedef struct
5295 {
5296  dm_prim_t type;
5297  BD_ADDR_T bd_addr; /* Bluetooth Device Address */
5298  uint16_t num_states; /* Number of states in list */
5299  LP_POWERSTATE_T *states; /* Table of power states */
5300 } DM_LP_WRITE_POWERSTATES_REQ_T;
5301 
5302 
5303 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5304  * PURPOSE
5305  * Generated in response to DM_LP_WRITE_POWERSTATES_REQ.
5306  *
5307  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5308 #define LP_POWERSTATES_SUCCESS ((uint8_t)0) /* powerstates set successfully */
5309 #define LP_POWERSTATES_UNSUPPORTED_MODE ((uint8_t)1) /* unrecognised LP_POWERMODE */
5310 #define LP_POWERSTATES_UNKNOWN_DEVICE ((uint8_t)2) /* unknown Bluetooth device */
5311 #define LP_POWERSTATES_BAD_TERMINATION ((uint8_t)3) /* last state duration not zero */
5312 #define LP_POWERSTATES_ERROR ((uint8_t)4) /* error described above */
5313 typedef struct
5314 {
5315  dm_prim_t type;
5316  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
5317  uint8_t result;
5318  BD_ADDR_T bd_addr;
