5320 
5321 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5322  * PURPOSE
5323  * Allows the application to modify role-switch policy for ACL
5324  * connection setup.
5325  *
5326  * The policy takes the form of a table of conditions and actions.
5327  * When the device manager is about to initiate a connection to a
5328  * remote device, or is about to accept an incoming connection
5329  * request, it walks down the table until it reaches an entry for
5330  * which all conditions are met. Role-switch policy for that ACL
5331  * connection is then determined by the actions specified.
5332  *
5333  * There are four condition criteria:
5334  *
5335  * 1) Minimum number of connections to remote slaves.
5336  * 2) Minimum number of connections to remote masters.
5337  * 3) Minimum number of connections to remote unsniffed masters.
5338  * 4) Minimum number of connections.
5339  *
5340  * Each entry in the table specifies separately the minimum number of
5341  * existing connections for each individual condition to be met. So the
5342  * resolution operator for each condition is always >= 'greater than
5343  * or equal to'.
5344  *
5345  * There are two actions:
5346  *
5347  * 1) Accept incoming connection with role-switch (becoming master).
5348  * 2) Request outgoing connection, prohibiting role-switch (staying master).
5349  *
5350  * Either, both, or neither action can be set for any specified
5351  * combination of conditions. If an action isn't specified, then the
5352  * reverse happens, i.e. outgoing connections are requested allowing
5353  * role-switch and incoming connections are accepted without requesting
5354  * role-switch.
5355  *
5356  * Encoding
5357  * Each 'row' in the table is encoded into a single uint16.
5358  * Each condition is encoded into 3 bits, giving a range of 0-7.
5359  * Each action is encoded into 1 bit - setting the bit turns on the action.
5360  *
5361  * Bits
5362  * 0-2 Condition - minimum number of remote slaves.
5363  * 3-5 Condition - minimum number of remote masters.
5364  * 6-8 Condition - minimum number of remote unsniffed masters.
5365  * 9-11 Condition - minimum number of connections.
5366  * 12 Action - Accept incoming connection with role-switch.
5367  * 13 Action - Request outgoing connection, prohibiting role-switch.
5368  * 15-16 Reserved - must be set to zero.
5369  *
5370  * There are macros defined below to make packing the conditions easier.
5371  *
5372  * Restrictions
5373  * 1) The final table entry must be 0 - i.e. 'always do nothing'.
5374  * 2) The reserved bits must all be set to 0.
5375  * 3) All table entries (except the last) must have at least one
5376  * non-zero condition.
5377  *
5378  * Operation
5379  * Subsequent valid tables sent will replace any existing table.
5380  * Sending a zero-length table will delete any existing table.
5381  * If the device manager does not have a table then it will default
5382  * to its legacy behaviour, which was to never prohibit role-switch
5383  * when requesting connection creation and only to request a role-switch
5384  * when accepting remote connection requests if there is already an
5385  * existing connection to some other device.
5386  *
5387  * Notes
5388  * The purpose of this feature is to help manage and hopefully simplify
5389  * scatternet topology. Using it for any other purpose is likely to
5390  * severely reduce device interoperability. In particular, prohibiting
5391  * role-switch on outgoing connections should be used sparingly, as it
5392  * may be that the topology that the remote device finds itself in is
5393  * even more complicated than that for the local device and the only way
5394  * for the connection to succeed is with a role-switch.
5395  *
5396  *--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5397 
5398 /* Bits reserved per condition */
5399 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_CONDITION_BITS 3
5400 
5401 /* Conditions */
5402 #define DM_ACL_NUM_SLAVES 0
5403 #define DM_ACL_NUM_MASTERS 1
5404 #define DM_ACL_NUM_UNSNIFFED_MASTERS 2
5405 #define DM_ACL_NUM_CONNECTIONS 3
5406 #define DM_ACL_NUM_END 4
5407 
5408 /* Actions */
5409 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_ACTION_INCOMING_RS 0x1000
5410 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_ACTION_OUTGOING_NO_RS 0x2000
5411 
5412  /* Reserved (must not be set) */
5413 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_RESERVED_1 0x4000
5414 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_RESERVED_2 0x8000
5415 
5416 /* Macro to encode conditions */
5417 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_WRITE_CONDITION(value, condition) \
5418  ((value) << ((condition) * DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_CONDITION_BITS))
5419 
5420 /* Macro to decode conditions */
5421 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_READ_CONDITION(policy, condition) \
5422  (((policy) >> ((condition) * DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_CONDITION_BITS)) & 7)
5423 
5424 
5425 /* Macro to encode complete table entry
5426  *
5427  * slv, mst, usm, con are the four conditions - enter a number 0-7 for each
5428  * rs_in - enter 0 or DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_ACTION_INCOMING_RS
5429  * no_rs_out - enter 0 or DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_ACTION_OUTGOING_NO_RS
5430  */
5431 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_TABLE_ENTRY(slv, mst, usm, con, rs_in, no_rs_out) \
5432  (DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_WRITE_CONDITION((slv), DM_ACL_NUM_SLAVES) \
5433  | DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_WRITE_CONDITION((mst), DM_ACL_NUM_MASTERS) \
5434  | DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_WRITE_CONDITION((usm), DM_ACL_NUM_UNSNIFFED_MASTERS) \
5435  | DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_WRITE_CONDITION((con), DM_ACL_NUM_CONNECTIONS) \
5436  | rs_in \
5437  | no_rs_out)
5438 
5439 /* Masks */
5440 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_CONDITION_MASK 0x0FFF
5441 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_ACTION_MASK 0x3000
5442 #define DM_LP_ROLESWITCH_RESERVED_MASK 0xC000
5443 
5444 typedef struct
5445 {
5446  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_REQ */
5447  uint16_t version; /* Must be set to 0 */
5448  uint16_t length; /* Number of uint16s in table */
5449  uint16_t *rs_table; /* Pointer to role-switch table */
5450 } DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_REQ_T;
5451 
5452 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5453  * PURPOSE
5454  * Response to DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_REQ.
5455  *
5456  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5457 
5458 
5459 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_SUCCESS ((uint8_t)0)
5460 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_ILLEGAL ((uint8_t)1)
5461 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_UNSUPPORTED ((uint8_t)2)
5462 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_NOT_ZERO_TERMINATED ((uint8_t)3)
5463 typedef struct
5464 {
5465  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_CFM */
5466  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */

5469 
5470 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5471  * PURPOSE
5472  * Maintain list of remote devices for which the Device Manager will
5473  * always try to become master during any ACL connection creation,
5474  * even if there are no existing ACLs connected.
5475  *
5476  * For locally-initiated connection requests to devices in the list,
5477  * the Device Manager will prohibit role-switch, thus ensuring that
5478  * the local device becomes master.
5479  *
5480  * For remotely-initiated connection requests to devices in the list,
5481  * the Device Manager will request a role-switch during connection
5482  * creation. This may or may not be accepted by the remote device.
5483  *
5484  * This primitive may be used to:
5485  *
5486  * 1) ADD a new device to the list
5487  * 2) DELETE a device from the list
5488  * 3) CLEAR the entire list
5489  *
5490  * This primitive should be used only to work around problems with
5491  * severely misbehaving remote devices. Any other use is likely to
5492  * produce a severely misbehaving local device and lead to major
5493  * interoperability problems.
5494  *
5495  * Role-switches should only be used to simplify topology. In most
5496  * cases, DM_LP_WRITE_ROLESWITCH_POLICY_REQ/CFM should be sufficient.
5497  * DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_REQ/CFM should only be used
5498  * when it is necessary to become master, even when there are no
5499  * existing connections, because the remote device is badly behaved
5500  * and will not role-switch after connection creation and it is likely
5501  * that further ACLs will soon be connected. (If it turns out that
5502  * no further ACLs materialise after a connection affected by the
5503  * device list is created then the local device might want to
5504  * consider initiating a role-switch to become slave.)
5505  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5506 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_CLEAR 0x0000
5507 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_ADD 0x0001
5508 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_DELETE 0x0002
5509 typedef struct
5510 {
5511  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_REQ */
5512  uint16_t operation; /* ADD, DELETE, CLEAR. */
5513  BD_ADDR_T bd_addr; /* Pointer to array of Bluetooth addresses. */
5514 } DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_REQ_T;
5515 
5516 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_SUCCESS 0x00
5517 #define DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_ILLEGAL 0x01
5518 typedef struct
5519 {
5520  dm_prim_t type; /* Always DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_CFM */
5521  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
5522  uint8_t status; /* Indication of success or failure */
5523 } DM_LP_WRITE_ALWAYS_MASTER_DEVICES_CFM_T;

6755 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6756  * API:
6757  * DM_HCI_ULP_SET_ADVERTISING_PARAMETERS_REQ_T
6758  *
6759  * PURPOSE:
6760  * This API sets advertisement parameters to the Host and Controller.
6761  * There is a set of applicable parameters for a given advertising_type.
6762  * Only the applicable parameters would be considered for the setting.
6763  * All other parameters would be ignored at both Host and Controller.
6764  *
6765  * This API can fail for invalid advertising parameter or when HCI set
6766  * advertise enable command for "ENABLE" operation is in progress or
6767  * advertising is already enabled.
6768  *
6769  * Upon every successful attempt to set advertisement parameters either through
6770  * DM_HCI_ULP_SET_ADVERTISING_PARAMETERS_REQ or through ATT_CONNECT_REQ,
6771  * an event (DM_ULP_ADV_PARAM_UPDATE_IND) will be generted. It is strongly
6772  * recommended that succeeding attempts to modify these parameters be
6773  * triggered only after DM_ULP_ADV_PARAM_UPDATE_IND has been received.
6774  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
6775 typedef HCI_ULP_SET_ADVERTISING_PARAMETERS_T DM_HCI_ULP_SET_ADVERTISING_PARAMETERS_REQ_T;

6942  * after a LE connection is established.

6945  * just after receiveing DM_ACL_OPENED_IND.
6946  * Application may choose to enable specific services (isochronous service)
6947  * based on the channel selection algorithm used at controller.
6948  *
6949  * Following are the possible values for channel_selection_algorithm param :
6950  * value : 0x00 (LE channel selection algorithm #1)

6988 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6989  * PURPOSE
6990  * Provides an API to allow an application to update change the
6991  * Link Layer connection parameters of a connection.
6992  *
6993  * If the controller supports the Connection Parameter Request Procedure, an
6994  * HCI command will be invoked to trigger the Link Layer procedure to update
6995  * the connection parameters.
6996  *
6997  * For LE slave : If the remote device does not support or rejects the
6998  * Link Layer procedure, the L2CAP signalling procedure to update the parameters
6999  * will be attempted as a fallback.
7000  * In both these cases note that receiving
7001  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM_T could only mean that parameters
7002  * are accepted/rejected between Link Layer or L2CAP layers.
7003  * If accepted, confirmation does not mean that parameters has been applied
7004  * at the link layer. It is DM_HCI_ULP_CONNECTION_UPDATE_COMPLETE_IND which
7005  * informs the the new parameter values. Order of arrival of
7006  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM_T and
7007  * DM_HCI_ULP_CONNECTION_UPDATE_COMPLETE_IND is not fixed.
7008  *
7009  * For LE master : If the remote device does not support or rejects the
7010  * Connection Parameter Request Link Layer Procedure, the Connection
7011  * Update Link Layer procedure will be used as a fallback.
7012  * In return, applications will receive
7013  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM_T preceded by
7014  * DM_HCI_ULP_CONNECTION_UPDATE_COMPLETE_IND.
7015  *
7016  * RETURNS
7017  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM_T
7018  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7019 
7020 typedef HCI_ULP_CONNECTION_UPDATE_T DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_REQ_T;
7021 
7022 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7023  * PURPOSE
7024  * Provides parameter update confirmation for the request
7025  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_REQ_T.
7026  * For additional information, please refer to
7027  * DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_REQ_T.
7028  *
7029  * RETURNS
7030  * None
7031  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7032 typedef struct
7033 {
7034  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM */
7035  phandle_t phandle;/* destination phandle */
7036  uint8_t status;
7037  TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt;
7038 } DM_BLE_UPDATE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_CFM_T;

7114 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7115  * PURPOSE
7116  * Provides an API to allow an application to reserve LT_ADDR for CSB.
7117  * Reserving LT_ADDR much early will increase the possibility of LT_ADDR
7118  * availability.

7452 typedef DM_HCI_STANDARD_COMMAND_CFM_T DM_HCI_START_SYNCHRONIZATION_TRAIN_CFM_T;

7455 
7456 /* Physical rate */
7457 typedef uint8_t phy_rate_t;
7458 
7459 /* Following are the valid phy_rate_t values that can be supplied to
7460  * the downstream DM_ULP_PHY APIs based on application's PHY preferences
7461  * for a connection or as default preference*/
7462 
7463 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MIN ((uint8_t) 0x00)
7464 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_125K ((uint8_t) 0x01) /* Coded PHY, S=8 */
7465 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_500K ((uint8_t) 0x02) /* Coded PHY, S=2 */
7466 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_1M ((uint8_t) 0x03) /* Uncoded PHY */
7467 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_2M ((uint8_t) 0x04) /* Uncoded PHY */
7468 #define DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MAX ((uint8_t) 0xff)
7469 
7470 /* Physical type */
7471 typedef uint8_t phy_type_t;
7472 
7473 /* Following are the valid phy_type_t values that are used to indicate
7474  * PHY type of a link.
7475  */
7476 #define DM_ULP_PHY_TYPE_1M ((uint8_t) 0x01) /* Uncoded PHY */
7477 #define DM_ULP_PHY_TYPE_2M ((uint8_t) 0x02) /* Uncoded PHY */
7478 #define DM_ULP_PHY_TYPE_CODED ((uint8_t) 0x03) /* Coded PHY */
7479 
7480 
7481 /* Additional physical preferences, reserved for now shall be set to zero */
7482 typedef uint8_t phy_pref_t;
7483 
7484 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7485  * PURPOSE
7486  *
7487  * This API allows applications to provide PHY preferences for a given
7488  * connection on LE transport. Preferences for physical rate can be set for
7489  * both transmission and receiving side, this would help the controller to
7490  * decide upon an appropriate PHY. Bluestack would then indicate the actual PHY
7491  * controller selected using DM_ULP_SET_PHY_CFM. It has to be noted that
7492  * setting of PHY preferences doesn't guarantee the same PHY will be used for
7493  * the connection.
7494 
7495  * Applications should carefully choose PHY preferences depending on robustness
7496  * or higher data rate requirements. In case there is no PHY preference on
7497  * either direction of communication (rx or tx), minimum and maximum preferences
7498  * can be set as DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MIN and DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MAX respectively.
7499  *
7500  * Example usage of the API,
7501  * a. If user prefers to use either 1M or 2M PHY to receive data and
7502  * 1M PHY to transmit data then following values should be set.
7503  * min_tx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_1M
7504  * max_tx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_1M
7505  * min_rx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_1M
7506  * max_rx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_2M
7507  * In this case controller may initiate LL procedure to request PHY update
7508  * to use 2M PHY for rx.
7509  *
7510  * b. If user prefers to use coded PHY s=8 for transmission and if it has
7511  * no preference for receiving side then following values should be set.
7512  * min_tx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_125K
7513  * max_tx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_125K
7514  * min_rx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MIN
7515  * max_rx = DM_ULP_PHY_RATE_MAX
7516  *
7517  * Note:
7518  * 1. Local controller or remote device may autonomously trigger PHY update
7519  * because of various reasons, during such events DM_ULP_PHY_UPDATE_IND will
7520  * be sent to the applications to notify the change.
7521  * 2. Users can set PHY preference values only in contiguous range, preferences
7522  * such as 125K PHY and 2M PHY (excluding 512K,1M) is considered as
7523  * odd choice hence it is not supported in this API.
7524  *
7525  * RETURNS
7526  * DM_ULP_SET_PHY_CFM_T
7527  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7528  typedef struct
7529 {
7530  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_ULP_SET_PHY_REQ */
7531  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
7532  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt; /* transport Bluetooth device address */
7533  phy_rate_t min_tx; /* Minimum preferred tx rate */
7534  phy_rate_t max_tx; /* Maximum preferred tx rate */
7535  phy_rate_t min_rx; /* Minimum preferred rx rate */
7536  phy_rate_t max_rx; /* Maximum preferred rx rate */
7537  phy_pref_t flags; /* Flags for additional preference,
7538  reserved for now. Shall be set to zero */
7539 } DM_ULP_SET_PHY_REQ_T;
7540 
7541 
7542 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7543  * PURPOSE
7544  *
7545  * This event will notify the status of the DM_ULP_SET_PHY_REQ command
7546  * given by the application. Status value other than zero is considered to be
7547  * failure. Status being success doesn't necessarily mean all the preferred
7548  * PHY choices has taken into effect, rather it indicates either rx or tx PHY
7549  * or both has been updated.
7550  *
7551  * Note: Type of coded PHY (s=2 or s=8) is not indicated to application.
7552  * Type of PHY will indicate whether the link is on 1M, 2M or Coded PHY type,
7553  * ref : phy_type_t.
7554  *
7555  * RETURNS
7556  * None
7557  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7558 typedef struct
7559 {
7560  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_ULP_SET_PHY_CFM */
7561  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
7562  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt; /* transport Bluetooth device address */
7563  phy_type_t tx_phy_type; /* current tx PHY type of the connection */
7564  phy_type_t rx_phy_type; /* current rx PHY type of the connection */
7565  hci_return_t status; /* anything other than zero is failure */
7566 } DM_ULP_SET_PHY_CFM_T;
7567 
7568 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7569  * PURPOSE
7570  *
7571  * This event would be sent to application to notify the change in PHY of a
7572  * connection. Local controller may choose to update PHY autonomously
7573  * for various reasons, including remote device requesting for an update.
7574  *
7575  * Note: Type of coded PHY (s=2 or s=8) is not indicated to application.
7576  * Type of PHY will indicate whether the link is on 1M, 2M or Coded PHY type,
7577  * ref : phy_type_t.
7578  *
7579  * RETURNS
7580  * None
7581  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7582 
7583 typedef struct
7584 {
7585  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_ULP_PHY_UPDATE_IND */
7586  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
7587  TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt; /* transport Bluetooth device address */
7588  phy_type_t tx_phy_type; /* updated tx PHY type of the connection */
7589  phy_type_t rx_phy_type; /* updated rx PHY type of the connection */
7590 } DM_ULP_PHY_UPDATE_IND_T;
7591 
7592 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7593  * PURPOSE
7594  *
7595  * This API allows applications to provide PHY preferences for all upcoming
7596  * connections after this request is processed successfully. Usage of this API
7597  * is same as DM_ULP_SET_PHY_REQ, but the preference would be applied to all
7598  * subsequent connections.
7599  *
7600  * RETURNS
7601  * DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_CFM_T
7602  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7603 
7604 typedef struct
7605 {
7606  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_REQ */
7607  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
7608  phy_rate_t min_tx; /* Minimum preferred tx rate */
7609  phy_rate_t max_tx; /* Maximum preferred tx rate */
7610  phy_rate_t min_rx; /* Minimum preferred rx rate */
7611  phy_rate_t max_rx; /* Maximum preferred rx rate */
7612  phy_pref_t flags; /* Flags for additional preference,
7613  reserved for now. Shall be set to zero */
7614 } DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_REQ_T;
7615 
7616 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
7617  * PURPOSE
7618  *
7619  * This event will notify the status of the DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_REQ command
7620  * given by the application. Status value other than zero is considered to be
7621  * failure.
7622  *
7623  * RETURNS
7624  * None
7625  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7626 typedef struct
7627 {
7628  dm_prim_t type; /* DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_CFM */
7629  phandle_t phandle; /* destination phandle */
7630  hci_return_t status; /* status of set default PHY */
7631 } DM_ULP_SET_DEFAULT_PHY_CFM_T;
